124 "§34-19-14
125 (a) The board shall do all of the following consistent
126 with this chapter:
127 (1) Approve, renew, suspend, or revoke licenses for the
128 practice of midwifery.
129 (2) Investigate and conduct hearings regarding
130 complaints against a licensed midwife in order to determine if
131 disciplinary action is warranted.
132 (3) Establish reasonable licensure fees, including, but
133 not limited to, initial application, renewal, and
134 reinstatement fees.
135 (4) Develop standardized forms, including, but not
136 limited to, a midwife disclosure form, informed consent form,
137 emergency care form, and applications for licensure and
138 renewal.
139 (5) Impose administrative fines, not to exceed one
140 thousand dollars ($1,000) per violation, for violating this
Page 5

thousand dollars ($1,000) per violation, for violating this
HB128 INTRODUCED
141 chapter, a board rule, or a condition of a license.
142 (6) Establish levels of professional liability
143 insurance that must be maintained by a licensed midwife at a
144 limit of no less than one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000)
145 per occurrence and three hundred thousand dollars ($300,000)
146 aggregate.
147 (b)(1) The board shall adopt rules pursuant to the
148 Administrative Procedure Act to implement this chapter in a
149 manner consistent with the most current North American
150 Registry of Midwives Job Analysis and with essential documents
151 developed and published by the Midwives Alliance of North
152 America. The rules shall include, but not be limited to,
153 provision for all of the following:
154 a. Licensing procedures and requirements.
155 b. Minimum initial and continuing education
156 requirements for licensure.
157 c. Standards by which a licensed midwife shall conduct
158 risk assessment.
159 d. Standards for professional conduct.
160 e. A standard procedure for investigating complaints.
161 f. Requirements for clinical internships for
162 individuals seeking midwifery training.
163 (2) The rules shall ensure independent practice.
164 (c) A licensed midwife may not administer or perform
165 any of the following obstetric procedures which are outside of
166 the scope of the licensed practice of midwifery:
167 (1) An epidural, spinal, or caudal anesthetic.
168 (2) Any type of narcotic analgesia.
Page 6

(2) Any type of narcotic analgesia.
HB128 INTRODUCED
169 (3) Forceps or a vacuum extractor-assisted delivery.
170 (4) Abortion.
171 (5) Cesarean section or any surgery or surgical
172 deliverdelivery except minimal episiotomies.
173 (6) Pharmacological induction or augmentation of labor
174 or artificial rupture of membranes prior to the onset of
175 labor.
176 (7) Except for the administration of local anesthetic,
177 administration of an anesthetic.
178 (8) Administration of any prescription medication in a
179 manner that violates the Alabama Uniform Controlled
180 SubstanceSubstances Act.
181 (9) Vaginal birth after a cesarean.
182 (d) A licensed midwife may not perform either of the
183 following:
184 (1) Delivery of a diagnosed multiple pregnancy.
185 (2) Delivery of a baby whose position is diagnosed as
186 non-cephalic at the onset of labor."
187 "§34-19-16
188 (a) A licensed midwife may provide midwifery care in
189 the setting of the client's choice, except a hospital.
190 (b) A licensed midwife shall ensure that the client has
191 signed a midwife disclosure form provided by the board
192 indicating receipt of a written statement that includes all of
193 the following information:
194 (1) A description of the licensed midwife's education,
195 training, and experience in midwifery.
196 (2) Antepartum, intrapartum, and postpartum conditions
Page 7

(2) Antepartum, intrapartum, and postpartum conditions
HB128 INTRODUCED
197 requiring medical referral, transfer of care, and transport to
198 a hospital.
199 (3) A plan for medical referral, transfer of care, and
200 transport of the client or newborn or both when indicated by
201 specific antepartum, intrapartum, or postpartum conditions.
202 (4) Instructions for filing a complaint against a
203 licensed midwife.
204 (5) A statement that the licensed midwife must comply
205 with the federal Health Insurance Portability and
206 Accountability Act.
207 (6) The status of a licensed midwife's professional
208 liability insurance coverage.
209 (7) References to current evidence regarding the safety
210 of midwifery care in out-of-hospital settings, including a
211 copy of the most recent statement by the American Congress of
212 Obstetricians and Gynecologists on home birth.
213 (c) A licensed midwife shall ensure that the client has
214 signed an informed consent form provided by the board.
215 (d) For screening purposes only, a licensed midwife may
216 order routine antepartum and postpartum laboratory analyses to
217 be performed by a licensed laboratory.
218 (e) After a client has secured the services of a
219 licensed midwife, the licensed midwife shall document an
220 emergency care plan on a form provided by the board.
221 (f) A licensed midwife shall determine the progress of
222 labor and, when birth is imminent, shall be available until
223 delivery is accomplished.
224 (g) A licensed midwife shall remain with the client
Page 8

(g) A licensed midwife shall remain with the client
